WEBVTT

00:00:20.370 --> 00:00:25.430
We are going to talk about
your organization's first Macs.

00:00:25.430 --> 00:00:28.400
With me today will be Ian Kelly,
Senior Systems Engineer,

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:30.540
and we're also going to have
a short demo on some things,

00:00:30.610 --> 00:00:33.180
but I want to ask a
couple questions first.

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:37.500
First off, how many people have
never been to WWDC before?

00:00:37.530 --> 00:00:39.120
This is your first time.

00:00:39.280 --> 00:00:40.050
Excellent.

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:42.180
You're in the right place.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:48.440
Secondly, how many of you have never
administered Macs before?

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:49.960
Good, you're in the right place.

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:53.080
Welcome.

00:00:53.930 --> 00:00:59.030
When we get started,
we have some people that

00:00:59.110 --> 00:01:01.900
we want to talk to today.

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:06.410
We want to talk about the Mac user
in a Windows-dominated environment.

00:01:06.510 --> 00:01:09.030
We want to talk about
the Mac support staff,

00:01:09.420 --> 00:01:11.240
the island of Mac people.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:15.390
And we want to speak to you,
the Windows IT administrator who's

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:18.090
now been handed the Mac support.

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:19.850
What are you going to learn?

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:24.550
You're going to learn strategies for
gaining acceptance and offering support

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:27.240
for the Macs within your organization.

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:29.720
We're going to talk
about migration planning.

00:01:29.790 --> 00:01:34.220
We're going to talk about
building acceptance for the

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:36.300
Macs within your organization.

00:01:36.370 --> 00:01:41.070
And we're going to see with a couple of
case studies how others have done this.

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:44.600
What we're not going to learn,
this is not a full and

00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:46.850
complete deployment session.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:50.670
It's not a detailed integration session.

00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:52.620
That's not what it's about.

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:55.100
It's not an imaging session.

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:59.180
However, there are other sessions this
week that I urge you to go to.

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:01.120
You'll see them on the
slides a little bit later on.

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:03.360
For example,
the Directory Services Troubleshooting

00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:05.060
session later on this week.

00:02:05.110 --> 00:02:07.720
Excellent session and I urge
you to go to that as well.

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:11.410
We're not gonna talk about patch
management and this isn't a quick

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:13.480
and dirty shortcut way to do this.

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:19.400
We wanna give you real solid
strategies for supporting your Macs.

00:02:19.830 --> 00:02:21.870
So let's look at the Mac people.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:23.340
Who are they?

00:02:23.390 --> 00:02:25.000
Well, I'm one of them.

00:02:25.150 --> 00:02:26.410
You have a new Mac user.

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:28.930
It's an executive, maybe a superior.

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:33.400
They don't really have
a technology background,

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:35.400
but they have a Mac.

00:02:36.410 --> 00:02:38.520
They may not speak all the Mac stuff yet.

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:39.970
They may not call it a doc.

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:42.760
They may not really understand it,
but they've got it.

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:46.190
The value is placed on the integration.

00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:50.100
And if you're the IT administrator,
they don't care about your feelings.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:52.900
They write your check.

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:55.490
Make my Mac work.

00:02:57.890 --> 00:02:59.020
What they'll use?

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:07.140
Mail, Safari, maybe iWork, maybe iLife,
probably Microsoft Office,

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:09.390
and they may have a Mac at home.

00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:11.770
And as we're going to see
a little bit later on,

00:03:11.770 --> 00:03:15.390
if they have a Mac at home,
they're probably a local administrator.

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:18.500
and chances are in your
Windows environment,

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:22.510
you don't allow your Windows people
to run as local administrators.

00:03:23.170 --> 00:03:24.420
Not a good idea.

00:03:24.490 --> 00:03:28.500
So there's a little bit of
re-education that has to go on here.

00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:30.610
We'll talk about that.

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:33.850
The other set of Mac people
are the Mac Island,

00:03:33.930 --> 00:03:34.460
right?

00:03:34.630 --> 00:03:39.000
It's a small group,
maybe a graphic design group.

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:41.930
They're self-managed,
they're isolated from the

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:43.140
corporate IT strategy.

00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:47.180
They just, they don't get any
love from corporate IT.

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:51.100
and the Mac IT staff.

00:03:51.270 --> 00:03:54.040
Maybe one person, right?

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:56.480
Not supported by IT.

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:58.480
They're forced into the back.

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:04.530
At this time I'd like
to bring up Ian Kelly.

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:11.900
and Ian's going to talk about
the Windows side of things.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.980
Ian?

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:16.540
Thanks.

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:19.960
So how many people here before
we start are actually current or

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.900
former Windows administrators?

00:04:22.990 --> 00:04:23.390
Okay, good.

00:04:23.500 --> 00:04:26.860
So as Schoun said,
I'm a systems engineer with Apple Canada.

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:29.240
I cover the whole of Ontario up there.

00:04:29.240 --> 00:04:33.120
And in a previous life,
I was a Microsoft guy.

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:38.780
I spent my entire life doing NT to 2000,
2003 migrations, exchange migrations,

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:42.700
probably more migrations than
I can actually care to remember.

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:45.260
And now I'm a system engineer at Apple.

00:04:45.260 --> 00:04:48.440
So it's a transition that can be made
and can be made very successfully.

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:53.280
So what's the profile that we're looking
at for the Windows administrator?

00:04:53.390 --> 00:04:55.370
Typically,
you're looking at someone who is

00:04:55.640 --> 00:04:59.000
probably overworked and probably
spends most of their time doing

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:03.920
maintenance and or recovery rather than
looking at ways to push the boundary,

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:07.770
look at new technologies and look at
ways of making the working environment

00:05:07.770 --> 00:05:09.060
for users better and more efficient.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:12.690
A lot of time will be spent
with things like making sure

00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:16.670
that antivirus is up to date,
pushing out hot fixes and a lot of these

00:05:17.020 --> 00:05:19.740
will be happening out of hours typically.

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:23.880
So you'll be doing your nine to five
stuff and then working evenings and

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:28.650
weekends to do stuff on the servers when
you can actually have some downtime.

00:05:32.690 --> 00:05:34.840
and then there's Vista.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:38.590
So what's the typical environment that
the Windows IT admin is working in?

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:42.080
We're looking at, obviously, nowadays,
a large,

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:46.120
complex Active Directory environment
where things like group policies

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:49.840
are pushed down to users,
the desktop is managed,

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:53.910
and applications that can or can't
be launched and printers are set up

00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:55.710
and all that kind of stuff as well.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:58.520
There are some probably very
extensive security policies and

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:01.460
guidelines about what you can
do and can't do on the Internet,

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:04.500
what you can do with email and
what you can't do with email.

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:08.160
And typically,
you don't have much of a life.

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:11.160
And certainly, for my part,
towards the end of my

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:13.630
career as a Microsoft guy,
there was a lot of Mac envy,

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:16.550
seeing the way that things could
be done and seeing that maybe the

00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:18.420
grass was greener somewhere else.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:24.770
So what are the kind of questions that
IT management ask or obstacles they might

00:06:25.020 --> 00:06:29.160
raise and put in your path when you're
looking at this kind of transition?

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:32.040
Well, firstly,
it's always kind of a financial

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:33.660
human resources thing.

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:36.160
Well,
we can't afford to hire any more staff

00:06:36.310 --> 00:06:38.330
and you can't find these Mac guys.

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:40.910
Where do you find a Mac guy
and how do they train them?

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:42.460
There's no training for this.

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:44.160
It's kind of a dark art thing.

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:48.070
And certainly we can't afford to
double our resources and have a whole

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:51.260
bunch of Windows guys and a whole
bunch of Mac guys at the same time.

00:06:53.470 --> 00:06:54.860
So what are the important things to know?

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:57.640
Well, as I said earlier,
the skills are transferable.

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:01.450
I spent seven or eight years as
a Windows sysadmin and I made

00:07:01.450 --> 00:07:06.130
that transition to understanding
how the Mac works pretty easily.

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:08.510
I mean,
the skills that you're understanding,

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:12.350
the foundations, things like networking,
are all completely the same on the Mac.

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:17.460
So once the foundations are solid,
the transition is quite easy.

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:22.950
I know a number of great Mac sysadmins
who used to be Windows sysadmins.

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:26.720
Especially anyone that's
managing Unix right now,

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:30.940
and particularly Solaris,
they make fantastic Mac guys.

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:34.130
And I have a customer
of mine back in Toronto.

00:07:34.410 --> 00:07:37.200
He has been using Solaris
for about 20 years.

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:41.420
And I spent a day with him to show him
just the little intricacies of how the

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:43.770
Mac is slightly different to Solaris.

00:07:43.960 --> 00:07:48.030
And he's never bothered me
with another question since.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:50.620
To highlight this,
I'm going to talk a little

00:07:50.620 --> 00:07:53.890
bit about a company based in
Toronto called Core Feature Animation.

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:57.050
They're an animation company and about
two years ago they did an animated

00:07:57.050 --> 00:07:59.240
movie with Disney called The Wild.

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:02.660
And they had a decision from the
start that all of the 3D animation

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:07.260
was going to happen on Linux machines,
but everything else was going to be Mac.

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:10.400
And it was the same kind of deal
that Schoun spoke about earlier

00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:13.450
that basically the head of the
company was a Mac guy and he loved

00:08:13.560 --> 00:08:17.520
Apple products and said we're going to
be using them wherever it makes sense.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:22.180
So they had around,
it was a two to one ratio.

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:25.310
They had 400 Linux machines for all
of their 3D and everything else,

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:28.130
all of the Final Cut editing,
all of the shape compositing and

00:08:28.210 --> 00:08:30.210
all of the systems administration.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:35.040
By that I mean like the production
scheduling and all that kind

00:08:35.040 --> 00:08:37.500
of stuff was handled on Macs.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:43.030
And their headcount was basically
one senior full-time admin for

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:48.220
the Macs with a half-time junior
and five senior Linux assistants.

00:08:48.220 --> 00:08:48.230
So they had around,
it was a two to one ratio.

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:48.260
They had 400 Linux machines for all
of their 3D and everything else,

00:08:48.260 --> 00:08:48.280
all of the Final Cut editing,
all of the shape compositing and

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:48.560
all of the systems administration.

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:52.570
admins and six full-time juniors.

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:54.830
So really we're looking at a
ratio of 2:1 on the machines

00:08:55.210 --> 00:09:00.880
with a ratio of around 11:1,
or 11:1.5 on the actual

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:03.590
overhead for managing them.

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:06.110
Talk about strategies.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:11.110
Now we're going to delve into some
kind of finer-grain strategies,

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:13.930
and I'm going to hand back to Schoun
to talk about the first of those.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:17.280
Thank you, Ian.

00:09:17.910 --> 00:09:22.940
All right, so the strategy that we have,
we have five reality distortion

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:26.640
fields that are sometimes
considered pain points.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:28.240
They're not really,
and that's what we want to do.

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:29.560
We want to dispel these myths.

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:33.410
We want to give you strategies and
offer you support techniques for this.

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:35.780
First off, we have networking.

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:41.500
Integration, Management,
Deployment and Security.

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:44.210
Okay,
so let's talk about networking first.

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:49.520
The myth, our network is fine.

00:09:49.710 --> 00:09:54.180
We run dynamic DNS,
file transfers are fast,

00:09:54.230 --> 00:09:56.140
we don't have any problem.

00:09:56.220 --> 00:10:00.390
Besides, the Macs need AppleTalk,
I still hear this.

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:03.910
Today, the Macs need AppleTalk,
it's chatty.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.500
We use Cisco's VPN.

00:10:06.710 --> 00:10:08.260
What's Bonjour?

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:10.050
How does that fit within my organization?

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:11.620
Can I control it?

00:10:11.850 --> 00:10:12.660
I don't understand it.

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:16.600
And maybe the Macs don't
really network all that well.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:19.140
So let's talk about DNS.

00:10:20.050 --> 00:10:24.500
Dynamic DNS, it's great, it's okay,
works well.

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:28.240
How many people run Dynamic DNS in
their organizations now?

00:10:28.270 --> 00:10:31.930
Okay, how many people run Static DNS?

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:35.900
Okay, you're probably a little happier.

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:40.570
It's harder to manage,
takes a little more skill, but

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:43.940
Overall, it's a little bit better.

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:47.480
With a Mac, straight out of the box,
DHCP is fine.

00:10:47.770 --> 00:10:50.710
You want to have DNS in order,
especially if you're going to

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:52.090
be running Mac OS X server.

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:56.470
For example, if you're going to be
using static addresses,

00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:59.520
you'll need pointer records,
you'll need the reverse records.

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:02.220
Dynamic DNS may not always set these up,
you may have to go in

00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:03.420
and put them in there.

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:06.240
File sizes.

00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:11.410
A while ago, a few years ago,
I went to a large company in Islip,

00:11:11.410 --> 00:11:12.190
New York.

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:15.680
They had a NOC,
Network Operations Center,

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:17.660
about the size of a
football field underground.

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:21.340
It really,
Star Trek-like Network Operations Center.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:24.140
They had a graphic department,
they had a design department.

00:11:24.140 --> 00:11:29.780
And what happened was that the department
was complaining file transfers were slow.

00:11:29.780 --> 00:11:32.430
And they had, at that time,
a state-of-the-art server

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:33.760
sitting down on the NOC.

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:34.760
Everything was great.

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:40.010
But they had one switch for
the graphics department.

00:11:40.180 --> 00:11:44.570
So you had about 24,
25 Macs that were all

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:47.320
being piped through there.

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:53.660
All we did was ask them to look
at the average file transfer size.

00:11:54.130 --> 00:11:57.210
The Macs were 250,
300 megabyte Photoshop files,

00:11:57.240 --> 00:12:02.250
these really large files that were
being transferred back and forth daily.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:07.900
And the IT staff just didn't have any
idea because all the other files and

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:11.110
everything else were relatively small.

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:14.400
And just like most organizations,
those PowerPoint presentations

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:15.760
were attached as email.

00:12:16.040 --> 00:12:17.340
There was no limit.

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:20.170
Hey,
let's send a 15 megabyte attachment to

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:22.190
the person in the cubicle next door.

00:12:22.300 --> 00:12:22.500
Why?

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:25.850
Because we can.

00:12:25.850 --> 00:12:25.850
So,

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:30.400
When we showed them
that the Macs generally,

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:34.530
if they're in a design department,
they use larger files.

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:37.300
They all had a direct
line down to the server.

00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:39.240
Problem solved.

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:43.500
It's also an excellent strategy
for putting it on XServe.

00:12:43.650 --> 00:12:46.050
AppleTalk.

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:48.410
Macs can do AppleTalk for discovery.

00:12:48.420 --> 00:12:50.530
It's been deprecated, yes.

00:12:50.710 --> 00:12:54.320
They can't talk AppleTalk specifically,
but they can do it for discovery.

00:12:54.410 --> 00:12:57.150
And here's a little screenshot
showing that you can actually

00:12:57.230 --> 00:12:58.420
check it and turn it on.

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:02.060
And then we have the
Apple filing protocol,

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:05.100
which runs over port 548, all right?

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:09.780
Windows servers,
they just use AFP 2 old and busted.

00:13:09.780 --> 00:13:12.140
It's just services for Macintosh.

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:14.980
Doesn't work anymore with the new Macs.

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:16.780
You're gonna have problems with it.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:19.640
It's AFP 3.new hotness, right?

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:23.210
So there are a couple things
that we can do if you wanna

00:13:23.210 --> 00:13:24.720
do file transfers this way.

00:13:24.720 --> 00:13:28.950
First off, you can turn to SMB.

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:32.210
Mac OS X servers can be an SMB server.

00:13:32.220 --> 00:13:34.100
Macs can connect to SMBs.

00:13:34.100 --> 00:13:36.660
You can, if you need to,
you can transfer your files over SMB.

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:37.800
It's not a problem.

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:40.890
There's no client access licenses.

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:44.180
You may have some file name excitement,
right?

00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:49.280
If you've had Mac users that have
been using Macs since the 1800s,

00:13:49.390 --> 00:13:53.520
chances are they probably put forward
slashes for dates in the file names.

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:55.480
We know that Windows can't do that.

00:13:55.610 --> 00:13:58.970
So sometimes you have to
retrain the Mac users,

00:13:58.980 --> 00:14:00.780
don't do this anymore if
you're going to be transferring

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:04.120
these up to Windows machines,
here are the illegal characters you

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:06.080
can't use and so on and so forth.

00:14:07.230 --> 00:14:11.930
Also, there's a product called
ExtremeZIP from GroupLogic.

00:14:12.020 --> 00:14:13.740
It runs AFP on a Windows server.

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:16.920
They do file and print services,
they do clustered services.

00:14:16.920 --> 00:14:22.810
So if you can't get a Mac OS X server
in your environment and you can't run

00:14:22.910 --> 00:14:28.470
