00:17:28.360 --> 00:17:30.200
Bonjour.

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:32.200
Bonjour is based on zero-conf.

00:17:32.290 --> 00:17:33.810
It does four things.

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:36.440
Apple has it doing three of them.

00:17:36.520 --> 00:17:38.740
First,
automatic discovery of local resources.

00:17:38.950 --> 00:17:43.590
I have a printer, I have something else,
I plug it in, boom, it shows up.

00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:46.280
Automatic Address Assignment.

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:51.600
I get a 169.254 if I don't
automatically get an IP address.

00:17:51.650 --> 00:17:56.600
All Macs have 169.254
in their routing table,

00:17:56.790 --> 00:17:59.790
even if they have an IP address.

00:18:00.250 --> 00:18:04.040
In other words,
I can have two Macs on the same subnet.

00:18:04.160 --> 00:18:08.900
One of the Macs could
have a 172.16 address.

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:13.580
Another Mac could have a
24-dot something IP address,

00:18:13.580 --> 00:18:19.580
totally not in the same subnet,
on the same network,

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:22.170
and they can transfer files.

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:22.840
Why?

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:26.890
Because the 169.254 route
is in the routing table.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:28.680
It's hard coded in there.

00:18:28.720 --> 00:18:31.740
This is a tremendous advantage.

00:18:32.650 --> 00:18:34.880
Secondly, automatic name resolution.

00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:41.800
So in other words, we can put a name in,
just like Microsoft wins and NetBias.

00:18:41.950 --> 00:18:45.390
So we can do automatic name resolution.

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:49.430
Behind the scenes,
all the networking is handled by configd,

00:18:49.430 --> 00:18:54.160
that's the daemon that handles
all the networking in Mac OS X.

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:57.220
You can have multiple active
interfaces by default.

00:18:57.220 --> 00:18:59.480
I can have wireless active,
I can have Ethernet

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:02.590
active at the same time,
can have two DHCP addresses

00:19:02.590 --> 00:19:04.800
at the same time,
but I can have one static

00:19:05.110 --> 00:19:06.620
and one DHCP address.

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:11.050
And the interfaces can be reprioritized
without you losing connectivity.

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:14.430
For example,
if you have a VPN interface and you

00:19:14.620 --> 00:19:17.950
want all your traffic to go over VPN,
you can simply drag that

00:19:17.950 --> 00:19:19.340
interface up to the top.

00:19:19.350 --> 00:19:27.350
It'll remain inactive as
soon as you connect to VPN.

00:19:27.350 --> 00:19:27.350
It'll move itself to the top
and all the traffic will be

00:19:27.350 --> 00:19:27.350
pushed over the VPN connection.

