00:36:31.520 --> 00:36:36.230
Updates are somewhat hard to
manage and users download updates

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:38.840
before testing them and oh no.

00:36:38.840 --> 00:36:38.840
So,

00:36:39.270 --> 00:36:41.490
First off, with administrators.

00:36:41.670 --> 00:36:47.530
Mac users don't have to run
as local administrators,

00:36:47.530 --> 00:36:47.540
right?

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:51.100
If you do,
you can create neutered administrators

00:36:51.100 --> 00:36:53.100
in a couple different ways.

00:36:53.310 --> 00:36:58.080
One of the easiest is to edit the
Etsy sudoers file and take out the

00:36:58.080 --> 00:37:03.080
admin group and only put in the users
that you want to run the sudo command.

00:37:03.150 --> 00:37:07.220
So in that case,
they really can't get in there

00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:12.850
to run any commands as super user
because you've edited the file.

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:17.800
You can further edit the Etsy
authorization file to change rights and

00:37:17.800 --> 00:37:23.690
rules so that only certain users have
access to certain security policies.

00:37:24.180 --> 00:37:29.870
A third option that you can do
is actually put a second data

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:33.000
store inside the local machine.

00:37:33.100 --> 00:37:36.000
If you do that,
you can actually have administrators

00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:40.140
who don't show up in the system
preferences who may have a home folder

00:37:40.140 --> 00:37:42.160
hidden somewhere inside private.

00:37:42.160 --> 00:37:47.120
And that's a really good way to have a
hidden admin in there that's not really

00:37:47.150 --> 00:37:52.430
part of the original local directory
data store or any connected data store

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:55.840
like Active Directory or Open Directory.

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:57.480
Second, group policies.

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:59.640
The Macs can be managed.

00:37:59.700 --> 00:38:01.740
Apple calls them managed preferences.

00:38:01.820 --> 00:38:03.430
Windows users call them group policies.

00:38:03.460 --> 00:38:04.540
It doesn't matter.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:06.440
It's account-based.

00:38:06.490 --> 00:38:08.480
We can do group policies based on user.

00:38:08.480 --> 00:38:10.600
We can do group policies based on group.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:13.260
We can do group policies
based on computers.

00:38:13.300 --> 00:38:16.080
Or we can do group policies
based on computer group.

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:21.620
And we can be extremely granular in
the policy management that we do.

00:38:21.660 --> 00:38:23.750
And there are some excellent sessions.

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:27.980
Again, we're going to show them
to you at the end of today,

00:38:28.020 --> 00:38:29.630
but there are some excellent
sessions this week that

00:38:29.660 --> 00:38:32.060
I really urge you to go to,
especially centered

00:38:32.060 --> 00:38:34.950
around policy management.

00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:40.200
We also have integrated management.

00:38:40.270 --> 00:38:41.940
In other words,
we can have a Mac OS X server and we

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:43.500
can have an Active Directory server.

00:38:43.500 --> 00:38:46.800
And this is also known
maybe as the magic triangle.

00:38:46.840 --> 00:38:51.740
And basically what happens is
that we have a Mac OS X server,

00:38:51.860 --> 00:38:57.500
we bind it to Active Directory,
we create a group,

00:38:57.600 --> 00:39:02.150
we take all the users from
Active Directory and we nest them

00:39:02.150 --> 00:39:05.260
inside of the Open Directory group.

00:39:05.370 --> 00:39:09.990
We then do group policy management
on the Open Directory group,

00:39:09.990 --> 00:39:11.960
but we don't touch the
Active Directory users.

00:39:12.110 --> 00:39:14.460
The Active Directory schema
has not been modified.

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:16.380
We haven't had to make any changes.

00:39:16.570 --> 00:39:20.460
We just have a Mac OS X server
in the middle doing all of

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:22.740
our policy management for us.

00:39:24.180 --> 00:39:26.340
So how do we update the Mac?

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:30.800
Well, we probably don't want to let
users update their own machines.

00:39:30.830 --> 00:39:33.900
Windows administrators certainly
don't do this with Windows.

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:37.980
They have a centralized server
that they use for updating.

00:39:38.290 --> 00:39:42.160
And we want to thoroughly
test these updates beforehand.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:46.900
And how do we track what updates
have actually been applied?

00:39:47.050 --> 00:39:52.400
Well, there are a variety of ways that
we can push out software updates.

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:54.870
Apple has a software update service
that we're going to be talking

00:39:54.880 --> 00:39:55.820
about in just a couple slides.

00:39:56.700 --> 00:40:00.700
We can use Apple Remote Desktop to
actually push out packages.

00:40:00.700 --> 00:40:03.300
And there are a plethora
of third-party tools,

00:40:03.480 --> 00:40:06.700
Casper, LandRev, FileWave, Puppet,
RadMine.

00:40:06.880 --> 00:40:12.790
Some of these are open source tools,
some of these are pay-for tools,

00:40:12.810 --> 00:40:17.680
and this by no means is the only list.

00:40:17.680 --> 00:40:17.680
There are others.

00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:21.500
So here's a screenshot of Apple's
software update service and if

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:24.890
you take a look at the screenshot,
this is a Mac OS X server.

00:40:24.920 --> 00:40:26.330
It was connected to the internet.

00:40:26.500 --> 00:40:31.360
It went out to the internet and
it downloaded every conceivable

00:40:31.540 --> 00:40:36.860
possible software update known to
man over the past X number of days.

00:40:36.980 --> 00:40:39.610
It stores them on the server.

00:40:39.930 --> 00:40:44.510
Then all we do is tell our managed
Macs when they run software

00:40:44.510 --> 00:40:47.300
update to look at our server.

00:40:47.410 --> 00:40:51.730
This is great for education where you
may have a fractional T1 line or a

00:40:51.730 --> 00:40:56.320
small connection to the internet and
Apple releases an update on iLife or

00:40:56.420 --> 00:41:01.520
iWork and you have 200 Macs all going
out to get the exact same update.

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:05.120
Why not put a
Mac West End server in the mix,

00:41:05.350 --> 00:41:10.300
have it hosted and have all
that file traffic done locally,

00:41:10.360 --> 00:41:12.750
not saturating your internet line?

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:15.340
Oh, and by the way,
there's no client access fees for this.

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:18.700
You just buy the server and hook it up.

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:22.350
Again, the scenario,
if we visualize the scenario,

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:24.880
we have the cloud,
we have Apple's bank of

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:28.940
software update servers,
and we have our lone

00:41:28.940 --> 00:41:32.640
Apple software update server.

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:37.700
It connects, goes out to the internet,
and all of our Macs then receive

00:41:37.700 --> 00:41:40.330
the updates from our lone server.

00:41:41.720 --> 00:41:45.530
So what's the strategy
here with management?

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:48.950
Use proper acronyms and synonyms.

00:41:49.250 --> 00:41:53.030
If you're trying to correlate
group policies and very granular

00:41:53.190 --> 00:41:57.720
group policies on Windows,
know the names on the Mac side.

00:41:58.600 --> 00:42:01.440
Don't get lost there.

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:04.810
Second, create a matrix of supported
management options.

00:42:04.940 --> 00:42:08.000
In other words,
when users open up Safari,

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:11.090
I don't want them to be able to do
this and this and this and this.

00:42:11.220 --> 00:42:16.380
When users open up System Preferences,
I don't want them to be able to click

00:42:16.470 --> 00:42:18.530
on the Network Preference pane at all.

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:21.280
I just don't want them to
be able to click on it.

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:23.300
OK, well, do you want that user-based?

00:42:23.300 --> 00:42:24.630
Do you want that computer-based?

00:42:24.710 --> 00:42:27.690
Do you want that based on a group?

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:29.730
How do you want to manage that?

00:42:29.810 --> 00:42:31.360
So create a nice matrix.

00:42:31.440 --> 00:42:34.290
Decide which management
settings that you want.

00:42:34.400 --> 00:42:37.100
Apple uses MCX,
Machine Control XML language,

00:42:37.160 --> 00:42:39.220
to store these policies.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:45.480
And acceptance for the Macs in the
environment often hinges on control.

00:42:45.550 --> 00:42:48.560
There is the myth that the
Macs can't be controlled,

00:42:48.620 --> 00:42:50.900
that they run wild.

00:42:50.900 --> 00:42:51.760
And that's not true.

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:55.590
They can be managed with a
high level of granularity.

00:42:55.720 --> 00:42:56.760
Support.

00:42:57.120 --> 00:42:57.700
Set those policies.

00:42:57.700 --> 00:42:59.490
policies.

00:43:01.250 --> 00:43:05.500
Second, make sure your users don't
run as administrators.

00:43:05.530 --> 00:43:08.130
I know you don't do this
in the Windows world.

00:43:08.630 --> 00:43:11.500
and third, the Mac OS X software updates
can be handled easily.

00:43:11.500 --> 00:43:13.450
Again, no client access licenses.

00:43:13.450 --> 00:43:16.730
