00:58:13.220 --> 00:58:16.020
Are you really sure you think
this is Microsoft Office?

00:58:16.110 --> 00:58:17.190
I don't think so.

00:58:17.260 --> 00:58:21.520
So there's a lot more security
built into the OS to prevent things

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:23.790
like your Trojans and spyware.

00:58:25.130 --> 00:58:27.510
Let's talk a little bit about migration,
but really the focus here is going to

00:58:27.510 --> 00:58:31.740
be the case study that I'm talking about
next because it illustrates the points

00:58:31.890 --> 00:58:36.070
in the next slide a lot better than
me talking for 10 minutes about this.

00:58:36.690 --> 00:58:40.170
The key to a successful migration
from Windows to the Mac is

00:58:40.170 --> 00:58:42.600
really based upon these factors.

00:58:42.600 --> 00:58:46.200
It's important that we get
buy-in and buy-in is not

00:58:46.200 --> 00:58:50.340
just like a CEO or VP level,
it's everything all the way down

00:58:50.340 --> 00:58:52.530
through IT and to the end users.

00:58:53.290 --> 00:58:55.490
Any kind of strategy
cannot involve data loss.

00:58:55.550 --> 00:58:57.940
You can't go in and say, well, okay,
you've got that system,

00:58:57.940 --> 00:59:00.080
that's all well and good,
but you're going to have to lose

00:59:00.080 --> 00:59:02.290
all that data or you're going to
archive it and we'll just start from

00:59:02.360 --> 00:59:03.690
scratch on this new system over here.

00:59:03.700 --> 00:59:06.300
And the whole plan basically
has to be adaptable,

00:59:06.370 --> 00:59:10.000
scalable, realizing that no matter what
you think or where you think

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:13.000
you're going to be in a year,
the likelihood is that you're probably

00:59:13.060 --> 00:59:14.390
going to be a lot further than that.

00:59:15.830 --> 00:59:16.790
And then reliability.

00:59:16.910 --> 00:59:20.940
There seems to be an overwhelming
assumption that Macs,

00:59:20.980 --> 00:59:23.440
because they can do
things more efficiently,

00:59:23.440 --> 00:59:25.190
that we don't need to do
it in the same kind of way.

00:59:25.200 --> 00:59:27.200
So we're going to deploy
Active Directory and we're going to

00:59:27.200 --> 00:59:30.030
have four domain controllers because we
need that redundancy and reliability.

00:59:30.040 --> 00:59:32.590
But if we're going to move to the Mac,
we're going to do Open Directory and

00:59:32.590 --> 00:59:35.300
we'll throw an old Power Mac G4 in
the corner and that can be our server.

00:59:35.380 --> 00:59:36.840
It's really not the way to go.

00:59:38.940 --> 00:59:43.110
Case study I want to use is the
Ontario Government Ombudsman.

00:59:43.150 --> 00:59:47.060
What these guys are is the,
they're the guys you go to to

00:59:47.120 --> 00:59:48.500
complain about the government.

00:59:48.700 --> 00:59:51.010
So as you can imagine,
they're kind of busy.

00:59:51.040 --> 00:59:54.440
They get a lot of emails and
a lot of phone calls and it's

00:59:54.450 --> 00:59:57.430
basically everything from,
you know,

00:59:57.580 --> 01:00:00.980
the city came out and dug up the
street and now got a pothole at

01:00:00.980 --> 01:00:04.910
the end of my driveway up to,
you know, wrongful arrests.

01:00:05.460 --> 01:00:10.730
They were a 100% Windows environment,
only 120 users,

01:00:10.730 --> 01:00:15.240
and they had four full-time
IT staff to manage those 120 users.

01:00:15.250 --> 01:00:20.500
And basically what happened is the
ombudsman himself came in and said,

01:00:20.510 --> 01:00:22.160
"I'm a Mac user.

01:00:22.160 --> 01:00:26.440
I have my nice MacBook Pro 17-inch,
and we are moving everything to the Mac.

01:00:26.580 --> 01:00:28.700
I don't want to see another
Windows machine in this building

01:00:28.700 --> 01:00:30.800
at the end of this project."

01:00:31.910 --> 01:00:34.010
As you can imagine,
the IT staff were kind

01:00:34.100 --> 01:00:35.450
of freaked out by this.

01:00:35.530 --> 01:00:38.740
I mean, literally, I mean,
the guys were nervous and worried.

01:00:38.740 --> 01:00:40.660
They're like,
I don't know anything about the Mac,

01:00:40.660 --> 01:00:41.960
but we don't have a choice.

01:00:41.960 --> 01:00:44.030
The guy said we've got to
move and it's got to work.

01:00:44.120 --> 01:00:45.200
So what do they use?

01:00:45.200 --> 01:00:47.970
Well, they had this custom
case management system.

01:00:47.970 --> 01:00:51.810
That's basically where every phone
call and every email gets logged into.

01:00:51.840 --> 01:00:52.970
So it gets used a lot.

01:00:53.050 --> 01:00:55.360
It's kind of the most
important thing they have,

01:00:55.580 --> 01:00:56.370
even above email.

01:00:57.520 --> 01:00:59.480
They use Microsoft Office extensively.

01:00:59.610 --> 01:01:01.700
They do have a lot of email.

01:01:01.850 --> 01:01:04.230
It's not untypical to find
users there with excess of

01:01:04.230 --> 01:01:08.500
50,000 messages and mailboxes
in excess of 10 or 15 gigabytes.

01:01:08.500 --> 01:01:09.880
There's no quotas.

01:01:09.880 --> 01:01:14.490
They were using Exchange Server,
but they had nothing in place to limit

01:01:14.490 --> 01:01:17.420
users' access or use of Exchange Server.

01:01:17.420 --> 01:01:19.380
And they weren't using roaming profiles.

01:01:19.380 --> 01:01:21.820
So everyone was basically locked to
the machine they had on their desktop.

01:01:21.820 --> 01:01:24.540
They couldn't get up and move anywhere
else or use a different machine.

01:01:27.530 --> 01:01:31.310
The strategy we used around
migrating desktops was that,

01:01:31.320 --> 01:01:32.990
first of all,
we need to get any user data that's

01:01:32.990 --> 01:01:34.220
on the client machines up to a server.

01:01:34.220 --> 01:01:36.050
We need to have this in a
central location so that

01:01:36.060 --> 01:01:39.690
when we move these PCs off,
we're not gonna end up with lost data.

01:01:39.920 --> 01:01:42.730
So that was a big job because
although users were told to

01:01:42.730 --> 01:01:45.340
store stuff on the server,
there was no real way of

01:01:45.340 --> 01:01:47.080
ensuring that they did.

01:01:48.340 --> 01:01:51.960
The other thing that the company
did was put the new iMacs on the

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:55.560
desktop alongside the user's PCs way
before they could ever use them.

01:01:55.610 --> 01:01:58.130
So they basically had this
Mac sat on the desktop off,

01:01:58.130 --> 01:01:59.450
not doing a whole lot.

01:01:59.650 --> 01:02:01.110
And that was a really good strategy.

01:02:01.110 --> 01:02:03.970
I think they were just doing it to
save space because they didn't have

01:02:03.970 --> 01:02:05.600
a whole lot of room in the IT area.

01:02:05.600 --> 01:02:10.020
But the users began to say, like,
when do we get to turn these machines on?

01:02:10.800 --> 01:02:13.670
And so it kind of was driving
enthusiasm and anticipation way

01:02:13.760 --> 01:02:15.340
before things were ready to go.

01:02:15.340 --> 01:02:18.480
And the other thing they realized
was that we can't do training

01:02:18.480 --> 01:02:20.100
as a kind of one-time thing.

01:02:20.100 --> 01:02:22.090
A lot of people,
when they're doing training,

01:02:22.230 --> 01:02:25.080
they send all their users off for
a day or half a day or whatever.

01:02:25.080 --> 01:02:27.610
And then that's really it done.

01:02:27.620 --> 01:02:31.290
They realized that it would be a lot
more effective to do small training

01:02:31.300 --> 01:02:34.910
sessions over a longer period of time
to allow things to sink in and the

01:02:34.910 --> 01:02:38.320
users to begin to kind of come to
grips with everything and then ask

01:02:38.410 --> 01:02:40.610
more questions at the next session.

01:02:40.780 --> 01:02:41.820
Thank you.

01:02:42.420 --> 01:02:44.210
and the other thing they did
was an on-floor walkabout.

01:02:44.220 --> 01:02:47.760
So when they actually went live,
they had two of the trainers

01:02:48.320 --> 01:02:51.010
basically on the floor at all times,
just walking around looking

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:52.180
for someone to have a problem.

01:02:52.180 --> 01:02:55.670
And what that really helped with was
that no one ever had to get up the

01:02:55.790 --> 01:02:59.160
phone and call IT or log something
into their help desk and say,

01:02:59.160 --> 01:03:00.230
hey, this doesn't work.

01:03:00.400 --> 01:03:03.720
There was someone basically with them
within 30 seconds because typically

01:03:03.750 --> 01:03:06.720
the solution was maybe a 20 second,
oh, you just need to click here or

01:03:06.720 --> 01:03:08.010
close this and open it this way.

01:03:08.700 --> 01:03:11.820
And that really,
really helped the user's level

01:03:11.820 --> 01:03:15.420
of satisfaction with the system
over the first two to three weeks.

01:03:17.480 --> 01:03:20.970
So what they did was they picked
key groups of users based on either

01:03:20.970 --> 01:03:25.820
the amount of usage or the level
of knowledge and understanding and

01:03:25.820 --> 01:03:29.900
targeted key areas first they knew
would drive excitement and enthusiasm

01:03:29.960 --> 01:03:32.500
throughout the rest of the organization.

01:03:32.940 --> 01:03:35.560
and they locked everything down
way too much to start off with.

01:03:35.560 --> 01:03:38.020
They knew they wanted to lock things
down and limit internet access,

01:03:38.070 --> 01:03:39.300
locations people could run.

01:03:39.400 --> 01:03:42.330
And so they really went overboard
from the start because it's a lot

01:03:42.330 --> 01:03:45.200
easier to back off and give someone
way more freedom than it is to come

01:03:45.200 --> 01:03:47.600
down the road three months and say,
okay, you can't do that anymore.

01:03:47.600 --> 01:03:48.360
You're not doing that.

01:03:48.480 --> 01:03:52.500
That's closed off and that's disappeared
from the dock because then people start

01:03:52.500 --> 01:03:54.750
to get a little bit angry about that.

01:03:56.700 --> 01:03:59.790
What we did was we took all of the
users out of Active Directory using

01:03:59.790 --> 01:04:04.100
built-in tools from Windows Server to
just dump a list of the users and groups,

01:04:04.270 --> 01:04:06.550
imported those users and
groups into Open Directory.

01:04:06.920 --> 01:04:08.930
They hadn't been employing
any kind of password policy,

01:04:09.020 --> 01:04:12.440
so every user had the same password
that they had five years ago.

01:04:12.440 --> 01:04:16.690
So we figured it was probably about
time for a password change anyway.

01:04:16.940 --> 01:04:20.070
And then they chose Curio
Mail Server as their new mail server.

01:04:20.100 --> 01:04:23.270
One of the reasons they did that was the
built-in migration tool will suck all of

01:04:23.340 --> 01:04:26.800
the emails and calendaring information
out of Exchange and put it into Curio.

01:04:26.830 --> 01:04:28.600
So there was absolutely no data loss.

01:04:28.620 --> 01:04:30.400
All their meetings and
appointments came through,

01:04:30.400 --> 01:04:34.370
the global address list came through,
and all their lists came through.

01:04:35.160 --> 01:04:38.380
They made the decision to move the case
management system off of SQL Server to

01:04:38.480 --> 01:04:43.000
FileMaker Server and write a custom
front end based on a browser interface.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:47.820
We suggested they might just want to
write a browser interface to SQL Server,

01:04:48.040 --> 01:04:49.700
but they were like, nope,
we're not having any

01:04:49.700 --> 01:04:50.800
windows in the building.

01:04:50.800 --> 01:04:54.580
So they worked with a local FileMaker
developer to basically rewrite their

01:04:54.580 --> 01:04:58.200
entire case management system for
FileMaker being cross-platform.

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:00.700
So if they ever need to go,
let's say the new ombudsman comes

01:05:00.700 --> 01:05:03.200
in in five years' time and he says,
what's all this stuff?

01:05:03.200 --> 01:05:04.310
We're kicking it out.

01:05:04.360 --> 01:05:04.980
They can move FileMaker.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:06.030
FileMaker across.

01:05:06.050 --> 01:05:10.130
And they wanted that flexibility of
not being tied to a specific platform.

01:05:10.970 --> 01:05:13.380
So they managed to get rid of
the access front end and replace

01:05:13.530 --> 01:05:15.800
it with a browser-based access.

01:05:15.860 --> 01:05:18.500
This is roughly what
it looked like before.

01:05:18.570 --> 01:05:23.400
They had basically a mismatch of
servers from different vendors,

01:05:23.400 --> 01:05:26.500
different tape drives and different
storage arrays that were individually

01:05:26.500 --> 01:05:28.950
attached and everything was kind
of split out and there was no

01:05:28.950 --> 01:05:30.280
real management to everything.

01:05:30.350 --> 01:05:33.090
Some of the storage arrays
were completely full and

01:05:33.090 --> 01:05:34.830
some of them were half empty.

01:05:35.260 --> 01:05:40.340
and there were a mix of 70 to 50 on
the desktop and laptop side things.

01:05:40.750 --> 01:05:43.810
That's what it looked like afterwards,
a little cleaner.

01:05:44.010 --> 01:05:48.350
So they moved to basically four XSERVs,
one XSERV RAID that

01:05:48.350 --> 01:05:50.400
stored all of their mail,
the case management system,

01:05:50.400 --> 01:05:53.060
and network home directories.

01:05:53.330 --> 01:05:58.580
They went to a tape backup using
Fiber Channel and LTO4 and went to

01:05:58.580 --> 01:06:04.370
the 20 or 24-inch iMac and the 15,
17-inch MacBook Pros.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:10.130
So as I said, they moved to a platform
independent case management system.

01:06:11.060 --> 01:06:13.870
They moved to
Microsoft Office 2008 on the Mac.

01:06:14.010 --> 01:06:16.700
They're using email way more
than they ever were before.

01:06:16.760 --> 01:06:18.660
They're now doing way more
with mailing lists as well.

01:06:18.660 --> 01:06:20.620
And they moved to
network home directories,

01:06:20.620 --> 01:06:22.940
which means if a machine
suffers a hardware failure,

01:06:22.940 --> 01:06:25.300
they just get up and move to
another machine or IT can just

01:06:25.360 --> 01:06:28.480
drop a new machine on their desktop
and they just turn it on and go.

01:06:29.960 --> 01:06:33.220
They imaged every machine in the
building in the space of one and a half

01:06:33.390 --> 01:06:37.280
days and they now have much greater
flexibility than they ever had before.

01:06:37.280 --> 01:06:39.910
Previously, if a Windows machine died,
they basically had to wait

01:06:39.910 --> 01:06:42.140
for a new machine to be built
and put on their desktop.

01:06:42.140 --> 01:06:45.220
Now they can just go to a spare
machine on the desk next to them

01:06:45.220 --> 01:06:47.360
if the person's on vacation,
fire it up,

01:06:47.360 --> 01:06:49.130
log in and they're good to go.

01:06:50.830 --> 01:06:54.400
The whole thing was basically once
there was three to four months of

01:06:54.480 --> 01:06:57.580
planning and anticipation about this
and once the decision was made it was

01:06:57.670 --> 01:06:59.140
basically eight months start to finish.

01:06:59.180 --> 01:07:02.560
It's handled by a local company
called Digital Transitions and one

01:07:02.560 --> 01:07:05.710
consultant from that company handled
the entire project on himself,

01:07:05.730 --> 01:07:06.780
on his own.

01:07:07.090 --> 01:07:09.670
They've gone to one
full-time Mac sysadmin,

01:07:09.670 --> 01:07:12.750
the other three are still there,
they're just employed

01:07:12.750 --> 01:07:13.580
in different areas now.

01:07:13.580 --> 01:07:18.220
And he was formerly the senior
Windows system administrator.

01:07:18.220 --> 01:07:20.300
He went on the training courses,
he picked everything up.

01:07:20.300 --> 01:07:22.450
And he's actually smiling now.

01:07:22.450 --> 01:07:25.380
I didn't see him smile
a whole lot beforehand.

01:07:25.900 --> 01:07:27.860
So that's really good stuff there.

01:07:27.860 --> 01:07:30.480
And they're actually now even
looking at buying another XServe.

01:07:30.490 --> 01:07:32.800
They're taking things and they
just wanna spread out again.

01:07:32.800 --> 01:07:35.400
And this is way beyond the scope of what
they originally thought they wanna do.

01:07:35.430 --> 01:07:38.090
They now start wanna looking at a
whole bunch of other technologies,

01:07:38.090 --> 01:07:41.030
run their web services
off of the Mac as well.

01:07:41.910 --> 01:07:44.140
So the strategy really was
around planning everything

01:07:44.140 --> 01:07:47.380
out properly from the start,
making sure that communication was

01:07:47.420 --> 01:07:49.040
with every level of the organization.

01:07:49.040 --> 01:07:52.710
It's a tempting thing to just work
with IT and forget everyone else,

01:07:52.710 --> 01:07:54.800
but they really wanted to keep
everyone in the loop and understand

01:07:54.800 --> 01:07:57.190
what was going on with the project.

01:07:57.750 --> 01:08:00.200
They had these great plans,
but we encouraged them to start small.

01:08:00.200 --> 01:08:04.190
I figured you're moving to Leopard,
you need to be very concise

01:08:04.200 --> 01:08:06.910
about what you want to do,
and you need to understand that

01:08:07.020 --> 01:08:09.400
when you're on the leading edge and
going with brand new technology,

01:08:09.400 --> 01:08:11.400
you need to make sure that all
of the other software vendors

01:08:11.400 --> 01:08:13.600
that you're working with are
also going to be up to date.

01:08:13.670 --> 01:08:14.900
So it's all well and
good going to Leopard,

01:08:14.900 --> 01:08:16.960
but you need to make sure that
Kirio are going to have a version

01:08:16.990 --> 01:08:20.060
of their mouse server that runs
on Leopard before you do that.

01:08:20.390 --> 01:08:23.700
There's a lot of ownership,
so they invited all the key departments

01:08:23.700 --> 01:08:26.300
in to understand that this is how
your new systems are going to work.

01:08:26.300 --> 01:08:28.230
Let's get your input on
how it's going to work,

01:08:28.330 --> 01:08:31.270
how we're going to develop this,
how do you need it to work for you,

01:08:31.270 --> 01:08:34.290
rather than just IT making those
decisions and telling the end

01:08:34.290 --> 01:08:36.540
users what it was going to be.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:42.090
Train them before migrating so that
users can get to grips with a Mac before

01:08:42.090 --> 01:08:45.200
they're having to use it on a day-to-day
basis and worry about their jobs.

01:08:45.200 --> 01:08:47.840
They can have a lot more fun
on the training sessions.

01:08:48.030 --> 01:08:51.420
And that's really the key thing
is to make sure that everyone is

01:08:51.500 --> 01:08:54.660
enjoying it because if it's any
kind of a chore or hard work,

01:08:54.850 --> 01:08:56.960
that project isn't going to work.

01:08:58.110 --> 01:09:01.200
With that, I'm going to hand back
to Schoun to round up.

01:09:01.260 --> 01:09:03.240
Thank you, Ian.

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:05.600
So the end result, don't fear the Macs.

01:09:05.780 --> 01:09:08.180
Embrace their oneness.

01:09:08.240 --> 01:09:11.480
Mac OS X, the simplicity,
the manageability,

01:09:11.530 --> 01:09:17.320
and the customization really
allow full integration.

01:09:17.410 --> 01:09:20.460
Strategic planning that's
based around the Mac's clear

01:09:20.460 --> 01:09:25.400
advantages make first-time
integration and migration much,

01:09:25.460 --> 01:09:26.900
much easier.

01:09:27.450 --> 01:09:29.400
because the Macs are better.

01:09:29.410 --> 01:09:31.080
I might be biased.

01:09:31.280 --> 01:09:34.240
So here are the extra
sessions that I really,

01:09:34.240 --> 01:09:36.280
really recommend that you attend.

01:09:36.320 --> 01:09:39.430
The portable home
directories coming up very,

01:09:39.430 --> 01:09:40.360
very soon.

01:09:40.360 --> 01:09:45.810
You'll see the extending and directing
or publishing directory services as well.

01:09:45.950 --> 01:09:49.240
So I would really recommend
that you hit some of these

01:09:50.640 --> 01:09:51.640
sessions and some of these labs.